<subSubSection id="7255FF5D569DBD9FCBF678F25E805054" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="1A16A3785CBB93FFD603A3D3DE09D089" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="30B4C9043F463BFBDA5F0BFFAAED2CCC" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
This species resembles 
<taxonomicName id="54408093FEA6D75C7085523C1C155D95" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Sphecodes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sphecodes shillongensis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="shillongensis">
<emphasis id="8C153CDA22A4C888BC9E763B26466E48" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Sphecodes shillongensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken id="5A1C99B32F86E61FF54A7637DB98DB94" originalValue="Blüthgen">Bluethgen</normalizedToken>
, 1927 and 
<taxonomicName id="6104CDA3394AA018A3525CE309121F59" genus="S." lsidName="S. simlaensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="species" species="simlaensis">
<emphasis id="E2E36BF467C2AF77E471BE47709F6482" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">S. simlaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken id="B7AEBDCBA614818358ECD8836F850B89" originalValue="Blüthgen">Bluethgen</normalizedToken>
, 1924, sharing a similar structure and sculpture of the body, including weakly developed antennal tyloids, a densely punctate mesoscutum and scarcely punctate metasomal terga. The species differs from 
<taxonomicName id="FD4C815046F23D919E20F466465BCACC" genus="S." lsidName="S. simlaensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="species" species="simlaensis">
<emphasis id="6C806EFBCFC83CBE76CC44AD85A331FA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">S. simlaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having dense facial pubescence obscuring integument above the antennal sockets; from 
<taxonomicName id="FA0B69722CCA207E59FB84AEA7F6F225" genus="S." lsidName="S. shillongensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="species" species="shillongensis">
<emphasis id="C93953E33212D978B4BFC9D22A057C02" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">S. shillongensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it differs by shorter antennae with flagellomeres (from F3 onward) ca. 1.1-1.2 times as long as wide (versus 1.3) and shape of the gonostylus with a large membranous part.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CB4433EB4A85FEAB72775490FA53F77D" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" type="descriptive notes">
<paragraph id="F295F40A516774F474ED763F32545924" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Descriptive notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="764BD0FA1BC678045B321B7FB3136D79" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
Wings hyaline; hind wing with angle between basal (M) and cubital (Cu) veins almost 90°, costal margin with six or seven hamuli. Preoccipital carina absent. 
<emphasis id="36FEBA53E5DAD19086D25B898F88BE26" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Male.</emphasis>
Total body length 4.5-5.5 mm. Head transverse, ca. 1.15 times as wide as long (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="4894696E4FF97C6CECB2B32ABE09C024" captionStart="Figures 28–33" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figures 28 - 33. Sphecodes chaprensis Bluethgen, male 28 antennae, lateral view 29 head, frontal view 30 T 1 - T 3, dorsal view 31 mesosoma, dorsal view 32 mesepisternum and hypoepimeral area, lateral view 33 genitalia, dorsal view. Scale bars: 1.0 mm (29 - 31), 0.5 mm (28, 32, 33)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.937.51708.figures28-33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/416779" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">29</figureCitation>
); vertex not elevated as seen in frontal view; antennae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="BFBE8D52B6746BC77CBB1B6B04983298" captionStart="Figures 28–33" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figures 28 - 33. Sphecodes chaprensis Bluethgen, male 28 antennae, lateral view 29 head, frontal view 30 T 1 - T 3, dorsal view 31 mesosoma, dorsal view 32 mesepisternum and hypoepimeral area, lateral view 33 genitalia, dorsal view. Scale bars: 1.0 mm (29 - 31), 0.5 mm (28, 32, 33)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.937.51708.figures28-33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/416779" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">28</figureCitation>
) short, attaining posterior margin of mesoscutum, F1 0.7 times as long as wide, F2 1.3-1.4 times as long as wide, remaining flagellomeres ca. 1.1-1.2 as long as wide; tyloids weakly developed, at most semicircular across basal 1/4 of ventral surfaces of last flagellomeres (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="4331577D8A7CEE23825E9234D73C69F1" captionStart="Figures 28–33" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figures 28 - 33. Sphecodes chaprensis Bluethgen, male 28 antennae, lateral view 29 head, frontal view 30 T 1 - T 3, dorsal view 31 mesosoma, dorsal view 32 mesepisternum and hypoepimeral area, lateral view 33 genitalia, dorsal view. Scale bars: 1.0 mm (29 - 31), 0.5 mm (28, 32, 33)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.937.51708.figures28-33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/416779" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">28</figureCitation>
); ocello-ocular area with minute punctures separated by at most a puncture diameter; face above and below the antennal sockets with adpressed white pubescence obscuring integument. Gena with sparser pubescence. Mesoscutum and mesoscutellum (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="F601DCE271FE2CB44ECC2B6C2309301E" captionStart="Figures 28–33" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figures 28 - 33. Sphecodes chaprensis Bluethgen, male 28 antennae, lateral view 29 head, frontal view 30 T 1 - T 3, dorsal view 31 mesosoma, dorsal view 32 mesepisternum and hypoepimeral area, lateral view 33 genitalia, dorsal view. Scale bars: 1.0 mm (29 - 31), 0.5 mm (28, 32, 33)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.937.51708.figures28-33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/416779" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">31</figureCitation>
) finely punctate, sparser medially (15-20 
<normalizedToken id="F6198003221D93BAB4AA96E4A2C1868D" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
/ 0.5-3), becoming denser peripherally; mesepisternum and hypoepimeral area rugose (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="E1B416B707A3FA00E33C5D41079578C7" captionStart="Figures 28–33" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figures 28 - 33. Sphecodes chaprensis Bluethgen, male 28 antennae, lateral view 29 head, frontal view 30 T 1 - T 3, dorsal view 31 mesosoma, dorsal view 32 mesepisternum and hypoepimeral area, lateral view 33 genitalia, dorsal view. Scale bars: 1.0 mm (29 - 31), 0.5 mm (28, 32, 33)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.937.51708.figures28-33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/416779" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">32</figureCitation>
); propodeal triangle (metapostnotum) shining, with coarse longitudinal-winding wrinkles; remaining surfaces of propodeum rugose to reticulate-rugose. Metasomal terga scarcely punctate (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="7FF06ED04F5DDCEC1E9F1E842FE646DE" captionStart="Figures 28–33" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figures 28 - 33. Sphecodes chaprensis Bluethgen, male 28 antennae, lateral view 29 head, frontal view 30 T 1 - T 3, dorsal view 31 mesosoma, dorsal view 32 mesepisternum and hypoepimeral area, lateral view 33 genitalia, dorsal view. Scale bars: 1.0 mm (29 - 31), 0.5 mm (28, 32, 33)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.937.51708.figures28-33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/416779" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">30</figureCitation>
); T1 almost impunctate, with a few minute punctures; remaining terga basally with tiny setae pores; marginal zones impunctate; T1 (apically) and T2 red, coloration of T3 variable; gonocoxite dorsally with impression; gonostylus as on Fig. 
<figureCitation id="64C9ABAC5724078B278A9A57D31EC701" captionStart="Figures 28–33" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figures 28 - 33. Sphecodes chaprensis Bluethgen, male 28 antennae, lateral view 29 head, frontal view 30 T 1 - T 3, dorsal view 31 mesosoma, dorsal view 32 mesepisternum and hypoepimeral area, lateral view 33 genitalia, dorsal view. Scale bars: 1.0 mm (29 - 31), 0.5 mm (28, 32, 33)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.937.51708.figures28-33" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/416779" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">33</figureCitation>
. 
<emphasis id="5420C08206DDB366684CB09A647AD06D" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Female</emphasis>
unknown.
</paragraph>
